{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17658160","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17658160"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:42:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:42:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20711"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20711","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20711"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.33,0.33,0.09,0.02,0.23]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13587"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96902"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13587","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13587"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20711"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79517"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11587"},{"type":"tags","id":"12524"},{"type":"tags","id":"12589"},{"type":"tags","id":"12590"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32668"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32669"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96902","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96902"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ESystemic emboli can originate from various sources and travel to different sites in the body, potentially causing tissue infarction.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most common source of systemic emboli?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Atherosclerotic plaques","Venous thrombi","Valvular vegetations","Aortic aneurysms","Intracardiac mural thrombi"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntracardiac mural thrombi\u003C/strong\u003E are the most common source of systemic emboli, accounting for approximately 80% of cases. Two-thirds of these thrombi are associated with left ventricular wall infarcts, while one-fourth are associated with left atrial dilatation and fibrillation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other potential sources of systemic emboli include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAortic aneurysms\u003C/strong\u003E - These account for a small percentage of systemic emboli\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAtherosclerotic plaques\u003C/strong\u003E - These can break off and cause emboli but are less common than intracardiac sources\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EValvular vegetations\u003C/strong\u003E - These can occur in conditions like infective endocarditis but are not the most common source\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVenous thrombi\u003C/strong\u003E - These can cause paradoxical emboli when there is a right-to-left shunt, but this is relatively uncommon\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EApproximately 10-15% of systemic emboli are of unknown origin. Most systemic emboli lodge in the lower extremities (75%) or the brain (10%), with the remainder affecting other organs such as the intestines, kidneys, spleen, and upper extremities. The clinical consequences depend on the vulnerability of the affected tissues to ischaemia, the size of the occluded vessel, and the presence of collateral circulation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Most systemic emboli (80%) originate from intracardiac mural thrombi, with two-thirds associated with left ventricular wall infarcts.","The most common sites for systemic emboli to lodge are the lower extremities (75%) and the brain (10%).","The consequences of systemic emboli depend on tissue vulnerability to ischaemia, vessel calibre, and presence of collateral circulation."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 4; page 131."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79517"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20711"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79517","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79517"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-03T12:45:31+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-03T12:46:05+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13587"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96902"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11587","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11587"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Haemodynamic disorders: thromboembolic disease and shock","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":3,"createdAt":"2025-02-26T15:17:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-26T15:17:52+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"18"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"12524","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12524"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Types of emboli","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2025-03-23T12:15:20+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-23T12:15:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"10"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"12589","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12589"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Embolism","synonyms":[],"description":null,"posi